article.description: Eddie Jones scored 23 points and Travis Best added 20, including four 3-pointers, to lead the Heat to a 93-84 win over the Atlanta Hawks on Monday night.
article.headline: Jones continues to star, Heat showing life
article.linkText: Riley seeing improvement as Heat defeat Hawks
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Pat Riley thinks his Miami Heat team is better now than at the start of the season. It's beginning to show. Eddie Jones scored 23 points and Travis Best added 20, including four 3-pointers, to lead the Heat to a 93-84 win over the Atlanta Hawks on Monday night. "I think we are getting stronger and staying stronger,'' Riley said. "I made a point before the game that we were always very competitive and played very hard earlier in the season, but we were just not good. "We didn't play well together and didn't run the system. Now they are competitive and in condition and I think playing the game better together.'' Rookie Caron Butler scored 21 for the Heat, who won for the sixth time in eight games. It was the second loss for Atlanta under new coach Terry Stotts, who replaced the fired Lon Kruger on Friday. Best made three of his four 3-pointers in the second quarter, as Miami took an early lead and, except for a 34-32 Atlanta advantage midway through the quarter, never trailed. Down 80-62 with eight minutes remaining, the Hawks made one final push, led by Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who scored two inside baskets and a free throw in the final three minutes to cut Miami's lead to 10. Best, known more as a penetrator and mid-range jump shooter, said he got some encouragement about his outside shooting from Miami's reserves. "I was hesitant at first, and then LaPhonso (Ellis) and a couple other guys were just like 'shoot it when you get it,' and the guys were rotating back to me, so I had space to put it up,'' Best said. Rookie guard Mike Wilks came off the bench to lead Atlanta with 19 points. Abdur-Rahim and Glenn Robinson each finished with 16. "We're still trying to get in the system coach Stotts wants us to play offensively,'' said Theo Ratliff, who finished with 12 points. The Heat led throughout most of the first half and built a 31-20 advantage on Butler's basket with 8:57 remaining in the second period. The Hawks countered with a 14-1 run but Best's three 3-point field goals in the final five minutes of the half helped Miami close the half with a seven-point lead. "We knew they had been playing zone the previous games they played, and we knew they were going to play a lot of that tonight, so we've been working on that quite a bit,'' Best said. "We've been feeling pretty good against zones, we've been moving the ball well, attacking the gaps.''

Game notes
Miami, which beat Boston last Friday, has won consecutive home games for only the second time this season. ... The Hawks, who rarely played zone defense under Kruger, used it on several possessions against the Heat.
